img.alt: Koochiching County is a county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. As of the 2010 census, the population was 13, 311. Its county seat is International Falls. A portion of the Bois Forte Indian Reservation is in the county. A small part of Voyageurs National Park extends into its boundary, with Lake of the Woods County to its northwest.

img.alt: Lincoln Parish is a parish located in the U.S. state of Louisiana. As of the 2010 census, the population was 46, 735. The parish seat is Ruston. The parish was created on February 24, 1873 from parts of Bienville, Claiborne, Union, and Jackson parishes, and its boundaries have changed only once (in 1877). This makes Lincoln Parish one of the Reconstruction parishes.

img.alt: Wright County is a county in the East Central part of the U.S. state of Minnesota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 124, 700. Its county seat is Buffalo. In terms of population, Wright County is the tenth-largest county in Minnesota and the second-fastest growing.

Cook County is the most populous county in the U.S. state of Illinois and the second-most-populous county in the United States after Los Angeles County, California. As of 2019, the population was 5, 150, 233. Its county seat is Chicago, the most populous city in Illinois and the third-most-populous city in the United States. More than 40% of all residents of Illinois live in Cook County.

img.alt: Carver County is a county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 91, 042. Its county seat is Chaska. Carver County is named for explorer Jonathan Carver, who in 1766-67, traveled from Boston to the Minnesota River, and wintered among the Sioux near the site of New Ulm. Carver County is part of the Minneapolis-St. Paul-Bloomington, MN-WI Metropolitan Statistical Area.

img.alt: Itasca County is a county located in the State of Minnesota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 45, 058. Its county seat is Grand Rapids. The county is named after Lake Itasca, which is in turn a shortened version of the Latin words ver itas ca put, meaning 'truth' and 'head', a reference to the source of the Mississippi River. Portions of the Bois Forte and Leech Lake Indian reservations are in the county.

St. Louis County is located in the eastern-central portion of Missouri. It is bounded by the city of St. Louis and the Mississippi River to the east, the Missouri River to the north, and the Meramec River to the south. As of the 2019 Census Bureau population estimate, the population was 994, 205, making it the most populous county in Missouri. Its county seat is Clayton.
